International Iributes to the History of Flight
First Solo Transatlantic Flight
The small, single engine monoplane, Spirit of St.
Louis, had been built to Charles Lindbergh's specifi-
cations. On the morning of May 20, 1927, its engine
sprang to life in readiness for the ultimate test - a
3,600-mile, nonstop journey from New York to Paris.
At 7:52 a.m., the plane lifted off the runway at
Roosevelt Field and headed into the murky skies over
Long Island Sound. Making his lonely way across the
ocean without a radio, "Lindy" had to contend with
storms, headwinds and overwhelming fatigue. Yet
he held out, and successfully landed his plane at Le
Bourget Airport near Paris at 10:22 p.m., local time,
on May 21. Instantly, he became the most famous
man in the world.
The full-color cachet shows the one-man Spirit of
St. Louis flying over the coastline of Ireland. The
plane was built in just 60 days by the Ryan Company
of California. Other manufacturers had refused to
sell Lindbergh a plane for the flight, fearing bad pub-
licity if he failed.
Mint Stamp: The mint stamp on this Cover was issued
by the United States in 1977 to mark the 50th anniver-
sary of Lindbergh's historic flight. It shows another
view of his tiny 28-foot plane flying over the ocean.
Postmark: This Cover was postmarked at Roosevelt
Field in New York on May 20, 1984, the exact anniver-
sary of the first solo flight across the Atlantic.
